<Layout title="IVF - In Vitro Fertilization">
	<section class="page-header">
		<div class="container">
			<h1>In Vitro Fertilization (IVF)</h1>
			<p>The most effective fertility treatment, where eggs are fertilized outside the body and embryos are transferred to the uterus.</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="content-container">
		<h2>What is IVF?</h2>
		<p>In vitro fertilization (IVF) is an assisted reproductive technology where eggs are retrieved from the ovaries, fertilized with sperm in a laboratory, and the resulting embryos are transferred to the uterus. "In vitro" means "in glass" - referring to the lab dish where fertilization occurs.</p>

		<h2>Who is IVF For?</h2>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Blocked or damaged fallopian tubes</strong></li>
			<li><strong>Severe male factor infertility:</strong> Low sperm count, poor motility</li>
			<li><strong>Failed IUI cycles:</strong> Usually after 3-6 attempts</li>
			<li><strong>Advanced maternal age:</strong> Especially &gt;38</li>
			<li><strong>Diminished ovarian reserve</strong></li>
			<li><strong>Endometriosis:</strong> Moderate to severe</li>
			<li><strong>Unexplained infertility:</strong> After other treatments fail</li>
			<li><strong>Genetic testing needs:</strong> PGT for inherited conditions</li>
			<li><strong>Fertility preservation:</strong> Cancer patients, elective freezing</li>
			<li><strong>Same-sex couples or single parents</strong></li>
		</ul>

		<h2>The IVF Process</h2>

		<h3>Step 1: Ovarian Stimulation (8-14 days)</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>Daily hormone injections to stimulate multiple eggs</li>
			<li>FSH medications (Follistim, Gonal-F) plus others</li>
			<li>Frequent monitoring: ultrasounds and blood tests every 2-3 days</li>
			<li>Goal: 10-20 mature eggs</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Step 2: Trigger Shot</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>hCG or Lupron injection to mature eggs</li>
			<li>Precisely timed 36 hours before retrieval</li>
			<li>Critical timing - missing this can cancel the cycle</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Step 3: Egg Retrieval</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>Outpatient procedure under sedation</li>
			<li>Transvaginal ultrasound-guided needle aspiration</li>
			<li>Takes 15-30 minutes</li>
			<li>Recovery: 1-2 days of rest</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Step 4: Fertilization</h3>
		<div class="card">
			<h4>Conventional IVF</h4>
			<p>Eggs and sperm placed together in a dish; sperm naturally fertilize eggs.</p>
			<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Normal sperm parameters</p>
		</div>
		<div class="card">
			<h4>ICSI (Intracytoplasmic Sperm Injection)</h4>
			<p>Single sperm injected directly into each egg.</p>
			<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Male factor infertility, previous fertilization failure, low egg numbers</p>
			<p><strong>Additional cost:</strong> $1,500-$2,500</p>
		</div>

		<h3>Step 5: Embryo Development (5-6 days)</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Day 1:</strong> Fertilization check</li>
			<li><strong>Day 3:</strong> Embryos at 6-8 cells</li>
			<li><strong>Day 5-6:</strong> Blastocyst stage (100+ cells)</li>
			<li>Not all fertilized eggs become blastocysts</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Step 6: Embryo Transfer or Freezing</h3>
		<div class="card">
			<h4>Fresh Transfer</h4>
			<p>Embryo(s) transferred 3-5 days after retrieval.</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Quick-results approach</li>
				<li>Body may still be recovering from stimulation</li>
			</ul>
		</div>
		<div class="card">
			<h4>Frozen Embryo Transfer (FET)</h4>
			<p>All embryos frozen; transfer in a subsequent cycle.</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Allows body to recover</li>
				<li>May have higher success rates</li>
				<li>Enables PGT testing</li>
				<li>Increasingly preferred approach</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<h3>Step 7: Pregnancy Test</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>Blood hCG test 10-14 days after transfer</li>
			<li>If positive, continued monitoring</li>
			<li>Ultrasound at 6-7 weeks to confirm heartbeat</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Add-On Procedures</h2>

		<h3>Preimplantation Genetic Testing (PGT)</h3>
		<table>
			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th>Type</th>
					<th>Purpose</th>
					<th>Cost</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td>PGT-A (Aneuploidy)</td>
					<td>Screens for chromosomal abnormalities</td>
					<td>$3,000-$6,000</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>PGT-M (Monogenic)</td>
					<td>Tests for specific inherited diseases</td>
					<td>$5,000-$10,000</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>PGT-SR (Structural)</td>
					<td>For known chromosomal rearrangements</td>
					<td>$5,000-$8,000</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>

		<div class="info-box">
			<strong>About PGT-A:</strong> While commonly offered, the benefit of PGT-A is debated. It may help select the best embryo for transfer but hasn't been proven to increase overall live birth rates per retrieval cycle in all populations. Discuss with your doctor if it's right for you.
		</div>

		<h3>Other Add-Ons</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Assisted hatching:</strong> $500-$800</li>
			<li><strong>Embryo glue:</strong> $200-$400</li>
			<li><strong>ERA (Endometrial Receptivity Analysis):</strong> $700-$1,000</li>
			<li><strong>EmbryoScope time-lapse monitoring:</strong> $500-$1,500</li>
		</ul>

		<div class="warning-box">
			<strong>Note on add-ons:</strong> Many IVF add-ons have limited evidence of benefit. Some may help specific patient populations. Discuss the evidence with your doctor before paying extra for these options.
		</div>

		<h2>Success Rates</h2>
		<p>IVF success rates vary significantly by age. In 2023, <strong>95,860 babies</strong> were born via IVF in the US, accounting for <strong>2.6% of all US births</strong>.</p>

		<h3>National Statistics (2022-2023 SART Data)</h3>
